Because I received relatively intense math training back in China, I can handle/manage to handle most of the STEM materials in college. Many people think that STEM students are smart, but from my own experience I would say that all my success, if any, are own to practice or training that cumulated since I was very young.
InhibitFactor: The most significant difficulty that comes to me is to figure out what I want to do after college. UCLA is such a huge school and it can be hard for freshmen to connect with seniors or others to seek help about future plans. For my first two years at UCLA, I was very lost and felt like there were only things that I didn't want to do. It is very hard to achieve anything when you don't even know what you want to achieve. Although through later exploration and by luck I was able to figure out my goal, it could have been so much easier if I was able to do so at an earlier time.

HelpFactor: Definitely parental support. Without them it'd be possible.

HelpFactor: Having a support group in my friends has helped me immensely.
InhibitFactor: Sometimes when I go to office hours, I'm scared to explain what I don't know to my professor in fear of being mocked or shamed for being behind. Thus, when I feel I am starting to get behind, it's just exponential because I'm too afraid to ask. Some professors I have had are impossible to keep up with and if you can't, they make you feel like you're too dumb to be in the major. I got a C in a lower division math pre-req for the Stats major(I had already taken a few upper division Stat classes averaging B grades) and I sought the Stats Academic counselor Lori. She told me that Statistics might not be the best major for me and told me to "consider" and easier major that had less math. I didn't-I'm graduating in Spring with at Stats degree.

HelpFactor: I think my primary education played a huge role in my success academically at UCLA. I come from a very wealthy, predominantly white school in Michigan, and it was one of the best public schools in the state. Thus, the teachers were really great due to how much money our school district had. My school offered many AP courses, so I was able to take many difficult and challenging classes that pushed me to improve my critical thinking skills, studying habits, and more. I honestly feel as though my high school was much harder than college, as I had hours and hours of homework every night, and I studied way more in high school.
InhibitFactor: Although transitioning from high school to college was a breeze in terms of academics, I had a much harder time developing a social life at UCLA. My entire first quarter my freshman year, I had no friends and was very homesick and depressed. I actually wanted to drop out of UCLA and move back home, and I felt like I made a horrible decision in going to what I thought was my "dream school." I feel as though it was because the town I was from in Michigan was very small, and everyone from my high school had their own small "bubble" that we stayed in for all K-12 years of schooling. I went to school with the same exact people for 13 years, so it was really hard for me to move away from this tight-knit community to an institution that is 10x the size. Eventually, though, I made more friends in one of the clubs I had been in since my first month of college, and from that, I was able to develop more social skills and pushed myself to make more friends in classes and other clubs.

Moreover, the workload that UCLA courses in this major throw at you in such a rapid pace requires a lot of time and energy. HelpFactor: At UCLA, I believe that a cornucopia of factors have enabled me to find success. Academically, my professors have been very approachable during office hours--especially Professor Tsiang, who will discuss anything, even if not related to the class--allowing me to feel comfortable in asking for help when I am not certain about a certain question or material in the class. Socially and emotionally, orientation established a few close friends with whom I can spend time and in whom I can confide if I have to talk to someone. These people have been the foundation for establishing a social group here at UCLA, which has allowed me to find success and feel at home. Furthermore, because of the diverse array of organizations on campus, I have been able to find my niche--through Bruin Sports Analytics, a club which combines my love for sports with my field of interest of statistics--and meet people with similar interests, expanding my community. Also, having a gym so close to the on-campus housing allows me to remain physically fit, which in turn boosts my energy and emotional state. Overall, I believe that the resources offered by UCLA--through the campus, faculty, students, and physical resources--have enabled me to find some success as I begin my college experience as a first-year.
InhibitFactor: Because I am so new to college (I have only been in school for approximately one month), I have not encountered any factors which have inhibited my success at UCLA in any aspect of "success." Obviously, the workload here at UCLA differs from that in high school, but that change was expected and I believe I am adapting to the academic rigor of UCLA according. Ultimately, I have not experienced any inhibitions; the people whom I have met have supported my endeavors and aided me if I was confused about some event or some problem.

HelpFactor: Friends and food.
InhibitFactor: Kind professors and RAs. And libraries.

HelpFactor: I wouldn't consider myself successful at UCLA. However, I do think I have been doing some things right that set me up for success. Having a small, close group of friends has helped me lead a balanced social life (even if the people I mostly talk to don't go here). Making clear what I know I want, and not caring about what other people thing (as best as I can) has helped reduce stress.
InhibitFactor: I think the greatest inhibitor of my success is my sheer lack of self-discipline. I would consider myself a very ambitious person with lofty goals. However, when push comes to shove I always falter and am never able to do my work diligently-- I put off assignments, studying, and exercising to guiltily indulge in escapism. This is really the main problem I have, and I understand it is a major one. If I can get myself to put in consistent effort, however little, I think I can make substantial progress as a person.

HelpFactor: In all aspects, having older friends that looked out for me my freshman year was really impactful. It's also because of her that I try to pass this forward!

But it's those same things I was scared to go to that had the best results. Academically, it's hard to stay on track and study because of how much social stuff there is to do.

HelpFactor: One part of my UCLA experience that's helped me succeed is finding a "home" through one of my student organizations, the Student Alumni Association (SAA). SAA helped create a structure I could lean on for support; weekly all-SAA meetings and committee meetings, supportive advisors, enthusiastic and welcoming members, and so on. It feels incredible to be part of an organization where I know people are cheering for me. When I'm down on myself about academics or mental health, I know there are people I can turn to to ask for help. That's definitely been a huge help for succeeding at UCLA.
InhibitFactor: I switched my major from Pre-Business Economics to Pre-Communications to now Pre-Statistics, and learning to work with students of these different majors has definitely been challenging. For example, in my Communications classes, students in my discussion sections were much more willing to discuss the course material than in my Statistics classes, where students are often much more focused on the homework and the grades. It's been difficult learning to work with students whose minds work differently and are focused on different things. This amplifies the differences in work loads as well between STEM and non-STEM classes.

We also take plenty of mental breaks during studying to recuperate and calm down by cuddling to release oxytocin and dopamine along with doing breathing techniques.
InhibitFactor: There are a lot of things in my life that inhibit my success at UCLA. Every weekday, I spend at least 2.7hours driving to and from UCLA in order to make it to my classes. This leaves me with very little time to spend with my family, partner or myself. Due to the fast pace schedule at UCLA, I find myself using all of my spare time continuously studying because I encountered my first midterms here and they are long and complex.

HelpFactor: I feel like the bruincast system literally saves my life at UCLA. I have a lot of pains and problems with my body that often prevent/ dissuade me from going to class. Bruincasted lectures allow me to not have to go to class when I am in pain. So helpful cannot be understated!

HelpFactor:
Having a strong network of supportive friends and mentors has played a large role in my ability to succeed at UCLA. For example, I had some health issues last year and one of my friends approached me and said she'd been dealing with similar issues. The issues were affecting me both academically and emotionally, and her support really helped me get through it. 

I've also become very involved with UCLA Hillel and Jewish life on campus. Through this community, I've made so many friendships and connections that I know I will have for the rest of my life. I've grown as a student, a friend and a leader, and I can say with confidence that I wouldn't be doing as well as I am here if it weren't for this incredible community.
InhibitFactor:
As a STEM major, I sometimes feel that I'm not getting as much support from my professors and TA's as I deserve.  For example, I had a math professor for Linear Algebra who, in many ways, discouraged us from asking questions. When we did ask questions, he often provided a quick one word answer and didn't fully explain his thoughts. This experience made it harder for me to succeed in this class both because it decreased my confidence and because it made it harder for me to receive guidance and feedback. 

Though I've had several STEM professors who are very good, I am aware that STEM professors tend to exhibit this type of behavior more than non-STEM professors. I'm not exactly sure how UCLA could address this issue, but I think it is important for students of all majors to receive the support they deserve.

HelpFactor:
1. Having a strong diverse community of ambitious and empathetic people in my network has probably been the strongest guiding force in helping me grow as an individual, team member and a leader in college. I am grateful for student organisations (I am involved with an entrepreneurship fraternity Sigma Eta Pi, a VC focused club in BV) for giving me a structured curriculum and social systems to help me develop diverse set of skills. I also lucked with amazing random roommates and floormates my freshman year, and have been lucky to be around people who genuinely care about communal good. 
2. Loving parents - I have changed my major three times now and my parents have been incredibly generous and supportive through all my indepentdent decision making. They have also given me free reign in picking out a somewhat novel career path (no one in my extended family has done investment banking) and given me the freedom to pursue internship opportunities that some parents might 
3. Abundance of resources and opportunities : being in a city like LA and a campus like UCLA has blessed with an abundance of resources (academically, socially and extracurricularly) to make myself a better human. I am grateful for all the mentor ship opportunities I have received, free professional development events, access to diverse communities, fantastic professors and fellow peers. 
4. General Education
InhibitFactor:
1. Exclusivity : The exclusive nature of certain campus groups can sometimes be an impediment in the way of more equitable extension of opportunities. 
2. Poor lecturing : I have strongly disliked over 4 classes at UCLA (with most of them being in the Stats department). Instructors that fail to communicate the core concepts make the class experience an absolutely dreadful one. It is really hard to sit through theoretical classes with professors that lack essential communication skills, and as much as I respect and value the role of a professor, it nevertheless makes it a frsutrating experience. 
3. Large Size of UCLA makes it hard to experience a lot of things

HelpFactor: Discussions have generally been very helpful academically, especially discussions for the Math 30 series. Review sessions by TAs and profs have also been helpful. Reslife social events have also been helping in socializing.
InhibitFactor: Some factors that have inhibited my success are the large class sizes and somewhat brutal class distributions for some classes. Another factor is just that everyone at UCLA is very high-achieving and seems to be involved in so many things at a time: i.e. it seems like the typical student at UCLA takes 18 units, has a job, is in a leadership position in three clubs, has an internship and a summer internship lined up, and can still make time to socialize. This can put a lot of pressure on me to feel like I need to be "keeping up" with other students rather than prioritizing my mental and emotional health. I highly recommend that students not compare themselves to others and do exactly what they need to do to live happy and fulfilling lives.

InhibitFactor: taking classes that aren't relevant to my interests but I have to in order to graduate (i.e. Japan 50). InhibitFactor: Lack of adequate racial, ethnic, and socioeconomic diversity in the student body and in the faculty for STEM. Lack of understanding for people from marginalized groups and classes. Excluded, belittled, and disparaged by my white peers several times during my first year, which is why I have not sought their friendship in the years since then. During my second year when I was in a lab group with two white students and one other Latino student, the white students would hoard the lab materials and do the labs on their own, and would not let us use the equipment until they were done with the problems they were working on. They also refused to share the lab's findings with us, so my Latino lab mate and I would have to wait until the second half of class to rush through the lab on our own and turn in our results. As for the very few times (I think just once?) that they did let us see their results, they just held the lab in front of our faces and counted down from 10 before turning in the lab and declaring "and it's gone!", knowing we weren't able to copy everything down.

FirstGen: Bad professors/lecturers, TA's who cannot explain their thought process, heavy workload for assignments, high grade weight on exams.
STEM: Being a minority student in STEM is difficult. Generally the STEM field is mostly white and Asian. There is a stigma of not being competent enough to join their study groups. Transfers are also typically shunned as well. This makes it very difficult to do well because the study groups helps students do well enough to maintain a certain grade, which raises the curve. Those students not in the study groups are at a significant disadvantage because they are testing against those study groups.
GPA: Transfers are not cared for like UCLA makes it seem before transferring here. Transfer student orientation is a rushed event that forces students to take unnecessary courses and confuses many transfers. Professors, students, and even counselors have made negative remarks regarding me being a transfer student. The only people who care for transfers are other transfers.
HighGPA: Lessen the weight of exams on grading schemes and teach TAs (and even professors) how to explain topics in an understandable manner. Students are always complaining about how confused they are after lectures because their professors can't explain topics well. (Speaking from an Engineering perspective)
- Less competition (curved-straight scale is fine, but curved scale pushes people away from each other, and drives students to isolate themselves in fear of helping someone that may do better than them)

-More appreciation of mental health (professors do not really care about anything outside their classes, unless it's a near death experience and do not realize it may be some of their classes that causes this madness)

I can clearly see that the Statistics department is much more aware of these points, and one of the reasons I am grateful that I switched.

FirstGen: Coming into college, I thought I was great at math. After taking math 32A/B, 33A, 61, I was mistaken. Just getting a B in these classes feels like such a tall task, they demand so much from you. The math exams here are comparable to reinventing the wheel.
STEM: Growing up in a typical Korean American household, academic expectations are always high. The parents expect six-figure salaries early in your career and they see any non-stem field as useless. Some anxiety issues have also complicated my concentration and study habits.
GPA: When trying to form study groups with peers in my stem (specifically math/stats classes), if a second goes by where I'm not 100% proactive and investing time in the other person while they aren't being fully diligent either, they pretty much drop you. The elitism here is really cumbersome, and my grades have suffered at times due to unsuccessful efforts in creating a lasting, effective study group. It just feels like you're being used simply for a grade, and once the class is over, that's that. They don't want to be your friend or make any outside effort to connect.
HighGPA: Back when I was deciding between colleges, UCSD was my other top choice. Admitted as a CS major, one thing I noticed was that their CS department is huge on having tutoring hours for all their CS classes, and fostering more student collaboration. This is valuable for gaining teamwork experience and students can only benefit from this by participating. TA and professor hours can be intimidating and crowded, so creating a strong, collaborative tutoring system would be great. Nobody there was cut-throat competitive or worried that helping someone else would "bring down the curve and thus disadvantage me." It'd be nice if UCLA could have a culture where students don't see each other as merely data points on a bell curve. UCLA could implement this system for STEM majors, specifically for mathematics and statistics majors.

FirstGen: I came from an ethnically diverse public high school, where I was valedictorian. Coming to UCLA, I had to work multiple jobs, deal with a broken skull, and become accustomed to the fast pace environment. I quickly realized that everyone around me was either "at my level", or higher. I personally knew people who could call their parents and get academic advice (parents were doctors who received their degrees in the States), others asked for money transferred to their accounts whenever they pleased. Some had connections and were quickly accommodated in research labs/ were able to work in professional settings. It was difficult for me as I didn't have that financial freedom or family members who I could ask for advice. When my first grades weren't as high as I've always been accustomed to, I began to lose self-confidence and doubt myself. It's taken a toll on me because I have been working these past 3 years to build my confidence in myself back up again. What is most heartbreaking for me is that I pour everything I have into my studies and, more often than I'd like, the grades I receive do not reflect my work. I look at other students and they seem to be having a blast/no academic issues/high GPAs. I just don't know what I'm doing wrong, and I really wish I did so I could fix it and be a higher valued student/competitive applicant.
STEM: I have been a NASA/outer-space fanatic since I was about 4 years old. Barely understood English but I would watch NASA documentaries day in and day out. Coming to UCLA, I wanted to study Aerospace Engineering. However, being a DACA student, there weren't really any potential job openings in that field for non-citizens. Coming here, I had to work at least 2 jobs, on top of being a full time student because I come from a low socio-economic background and my family was having financial difficulties. At one point, my stress/anxiety was so high, I had to resort to CAPS. Moreover, being a first generation student, the first in both my immediate and extended family to go to college, I didn't have anyone to rely on and had to figure it out on my own (resources/classes/lifestyle). I want to go into the Petroleum Engineering field, and as a first-generation, DACA, Hispanic female I feel that certain jobs like these prioritize males, especially white males.
GPA: Belonging: being a part of USP and mentoring through SWE. Lack of it: roommates in dorm didn't want to clean because they "didn't know how since they all had maids at home"; showing up for first day of lecture and professor stating "I am here to do research, not to teach. Research is my priority"; giving a presentation for my Thermodynamics (Chemical Engineering) class 2 quarters ago and the white male in my group kept cutting me off by rudely speaking over me(even though I was right and he was wrong), but he didn't cut off the other teammates (both white as well).
HighGPA: Inform incoming freshmen better (i.e. I had no idea one could be pre-med without being a science major); force professors to take teaching courses and to actually care about teaching the students; make homework more like lecture or make the lecture reflect what will be on homework (some professors only teach theory but the homework/exams are 85% application); make counselors more approachable (I've had bad experiences with them)

HighGPA: I think connecting the undergraduate students with graduate students for guidance would be very beneficial.  This may already exist but I think this is important.
